# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1901 Pittsburgh Pirates** finished in first place in the National League, 7½ games ahead of the second-place Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It was the first year that the American League operated as a major league, but there would be no World Series between the leagues until 1903.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team was managed by Fred Clarke, who was also their starting left fielder.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Clarke, in his fifth year as a manager at age 28, won his first pennant.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates won the National League championship in the next two years as well.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates were led offensively by Honus Wagner, who led the league in RBI and stolen bases.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Although the "Flying Dutchman" had never played shortstop in the majors until 1901, he appeared 61 times at shortstop that year in addition to spending time at third base and the outfield.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In a league that batted .267 as a whole, the Pirates outfield was notable for its hitting.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Ginger Beaumont hit .332, player-manager Fred Clarke hit .324, and Lefty Davis hit .313.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The pitching staff of the Pirates allowed the fewest runs in the league and was among the greatest ever.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The four top starting pitchers – Deacon Phillippe, Jack Chesbro, Jesse Tannehill, and Sam Leever – were the four top pitchers in the National League in terms of winning percentage.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] All of them were in the top ten in the league in ERA.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Future Hall of Famer Rube Waddell had pitched well in 1900 for the Pirates, but was sold in May 1901 to the Chicago Orphans.
[src:1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season/1901-pittsburgh-pirates-season] With a record of 90-49, the Pirates had the best record in the league.
